SIMPLE: sclaff
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sclaff
<hw>Sclaff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sclaffed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Sclaffing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Orig. uncert.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To scuff or shuffle along.</def>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>To scrape the ground with the sole
of the club, before striking the ball, in making a stroke.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sclaff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sclaff
<hw>Sclaff</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>To scrape (the
club) on the ground, in a stroke, before hitting the ball; also, to make
(a stroke) in that way.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sclaff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sclaff
<hw>Sclaff</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <mark>[Scot.]</mark> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
slight blow; a slap; a soft fall; also, the accompanying
noise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>The stroke made by one who
sclaffs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A thin, solid substance, esp. a thin shoe or
slipper.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sclaundre</ent>⟦br⟧
